body:
It's not clear how the current proposal interacts with [the first law of extend](https://github.com/sass/language/blob/master/spec/at-rules/extend.md#specificity). In particular, are an upstream module's selectors considered "original" when being extended by downstream modules, even when they were generated by extensions within that module?

Let's look at a concrete example:

```scss
// upstream.scss
.a.x {a: b}
.b.c {@extend .x}"

// downstream.scss
@use "upstream";
.c {@extend .x}
```

`upstream.scss`'s module CSS is

```css
.a.x, .a.b.c {a: b}
```

Once it's extended by `downstream.scss`, before any selectors are trimmed, it becomes:

```css
.a.x, .a.b.c, .a.c {a: b}
```

The question is, *can we optimize away `.a.b.c` here`*?

If all three selectors were in the same file, the answer would clearly be "yes". `.a.b.c` is a generated selector that's a subselector of `.a.c`, so it can be removed. But if we make the same decision across module boundaries, that introduces a case where it doesn't just matter what a module's CSS is, it matters *how that CSS was generated*. This is something we explicitly decided to avoid in other design decisions; see [the note on why `@extend` doesn't affect downstream modules](https://github.com/sass/language/blob/master/accepted/module-system.md#resolving-extensions).

That said, I still think there's a strong argument for allowing `.a.b.c` to be removed. Unlike downstream extensions, this is an *optimization*. That's the entire reason we trim selectors in the first place. The laws of extend are designed to serve as heuristics for when a given selector is "intended", as well as guidelines for our users as to what they can rely on. In this case they're suggesting that the extra specificity in `.a.b.c` wasn't intended, so I think it's probably safe to remove.
